        <!-- 1. Core distinction -->
        <h2 id="core-distinction" class="anchor-top">The Core Distinction</h2>
        <p><strong>The fundamental difference between AEO and traditional SEO is the success condition: SEO wins when a user sees and clicks your link; AEO wins when an answer engine selects your content and presents it directly, regardless of whether the user ever visits your site.</strong></p>
        <p>Traditional search engine optimisation operates within a familiar model. A search engine receives a query, evaluates millions of pages against a set of ranking signals, and returns an ordered list of results. The user scans that list and decides which page to visit. Your task in SEO is to produce pages that rank highly enough in that list to attract clicks.</p>
        <p>Answer engine optimisation addresses a different architecture. When a user asks Google "what is the capital of France" or "how do I treat a pulled muscle," Google does not simply list pages. It selects a passage from a page, or synthesises a response from several pages, and presents it directly in the search interface. The user may read the answer and leave without visiting any linked page. Your task in AEO is not to rank in the list — it is to be the passage that gets selected.</p>
        <p>This distinction is consequential. A page can rank on page one of organic results and still never appear in a featured snippet or AI Overview. Conversely, a page ranked position four or five can own the featured snippet for a high-volume query. The two competitive environments are parallel, not identical. Optimising for one does not automatically optimise for the other.</p>
        <p>For the related question of how AI-generated answers in platforms like ChatGPT and Perplexity differ from both AEO and traditional SEO, see our <a href="/geo-vs-seo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO vs SEO comparison</a>.</p>

        <!-- 2. Ranking units -->
        <h2 id="ranking-unit" class="anchor-top">Different Ranking Units</h2>
        <p><strong>In traditional SEO the ranking unit is the page; in AEO the ranking unit is the passage — the specific extract of text, list, or table that an answer engine surfaces as a direct response.</strong></p>
        <p>This difference has practical implications for how you structure and audit your content. A traditional SEO audit evaluates a URL holistically: its title tag, backlink profile, word count, domain authority, and overall intent alignment. A strong page ranks well or poorly as a unit.</p>
        <p>An AEO audit evaluates the content at a more granular level. Within a single long-form guide, there may be twenty potential answer passages: definitional paragraphs that could win featured snippet positions, lists that could populate "how to" snippets, tables that could trigger table snippets, and FAQ blocks that could appear in People Also Ask expansions. Each passage competes independently for its relevant query.</p>
        <p>This granularity means that AEO work is often focused on editing rather than creating: restructuring an existing paragraph so the direct answer comes first, reformatting a prose section as a numbered list to match the snippet format Google currently shows for a target query, or adding a clear question-heading above a passage so the answer engine can match it to specific queries.</p>
        <p>One well-optimised page can win dozens of answer positions across different queries. This makes AEO unusually scalable once the structural patterns are embedded into your content workflow.</p>

        <!-- 3. Key signals -->
        <h2 id="key-signals" class="anchor-top">Key Signals Compared</h2>
        <p><strong>Traditional SEO is weighted heavily towards off-page authority signals; AEO is weighted heavily towards on-page structural signals that make content machine-extractable.</strong></p>

        <h3>SEO's primary signals</h3>
        <p>The core ranking inputs for traditional SEO are well-established. Backlinks from authoritative domains signal that your content is trusted by others in your field. Keyword relevance — the alignment between your content and the specific terms users search — determines whether your page is a candidate for a query. Page experience signals including Core Web Vitals, mobile responsiveness, and HTTPS compliance influence ranking directly. Domain authority, built over time through consistent publishing and link acquisition, provides the baseline trust from which individual pages benefit.</p>

        <h3>AEO's primary signals</h3>
        <p>Answer engine selection relies on a different set of signals. Passage clarity is paramount: answer engines extract the passage most directly responsive to the query. Content that leads with the answer, rather than burying it in a longer discussion, is consistently preferred. Question-based headings create an explicit signal — the H2 or H3 mirrors the user's query, and the paragraph beneath it answers it. This alignment is a strong selection trigger.</p>
        <p>Structured data is more critical in AEO than in traditional SEO. FAQPage schema explicitly marks up question-answer pairs for machine consumption. HowTo schema structures process content for how-to snippet selection. The absence of schema does not prevent selection, but its presence significantly strengthens the signal.</p>
        <p>Conciseness matters more in AEO. Featured snippet paragraphs typically run 40–55 words. Voice assistant answers run shorter still. Content that delivers its answer in the right word-count range is structurally better positioned than equally accurate content that takes 200 words to reach the same conclusion.</p>
        <p>Entity clarity is also an AEO signal without a direct SEO equivalent. Answer engines need to understand precisely what your content is about to surface it for the right query. Consistent use of defined terms, clear subject-predicate sentence structure, and explicit entity references (naming the concept being defined, the process being described, the comparison being drawn) all help answer engines categorise and retrieve your content accurately. For more on entity optimisation at scale, see the <a href="/answer-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO complete guide</a>.</p>

