        <!-- 4. Content format -->
        <h2 id="content-format" class="anchor-top">Content Format Requirements</h2>
        <p><strong>The most visible practical difference between AEO and SEO content is structural: SEO content is typically organised to satisfy broad topic depth, while AEO content is organised around the inverted pyramid, leading with the direct answer before any contextual elaboration.</strong></p>

        <h3>Paragraph snippets</h3>
        <p>For definitional and explanatory queries — "what is X," "how does Y work" — featured snippet selection strongly favours content that answers the question in the first 40–60 words of a section. The answer engine reads the heading as the question, then extracts the first complete response it finds beneath it. Content that begins with preamble ("Great question! Let's explore what X means in today's context...") will lose to content that begins with the definition itself.</p>

        <h3>List snippets</h3>
        <p>How-to queries, "best of" queries, and step-based queries trigger list snippets rather than paragraph extraction. Answer engines pull ordered or unordered lists directly from the page. For AEO, this means structuring process content as numbered steps and benefit content as bulleted points, with each list item beginning with the key term or action. Long prose passages describing a process will rarely win these snippet types, even if they contain identical information to a well-structured list.</p>

        <h3>Table snippets</h3>
        <p>Comparison queries — "X vs Y," "best [category] for [use case]," "price of X in different cities" — trigger table snippets. An accessible HTML table with clear column headers and concise cell content is the target format. For traditional SEO, a prose comparison section and a comparison table serve similar keyword-ranking functions. For AEO, only the table is directly extractable.</p>

        <h3>Voice-optimised answers</h3>
        <p>Voice assistant answers impose the most demanding format constraints. A voice device reads one answer aloud, typically 20–35 words for simple queries. Content must be self-contained at this length — no "as mentioned above," no references to visual elements. Conversational sentence structure (subject-verb-object, no complex subordinate clauses) improves readability when spoken. For AEO targeting voice specifically, keep definitional answers to one or two short sentences and ensure they can stand alone without surrounding context.</p>
        <p>For a practical look at how these content formats appear in the wild, see our <a href="/aeo-examples/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO examples guide</a>.</p>

        <!-- 5. Measurement -->
        <h2 id="measurement" class="anchor-top">Measurement Frameworks</h2>
        <p><strong>SEO measurement is anchored in rank position and traffic; AEO measurement is anchored in answer selection rate and answer surface coverage — metrics that require different tools and a different analytical mindset.</strong></p>
        <p>Traditional SEO has mature, standardised measurement: track keyword rankings, monitor organic click-through rates in Google Search Console, and correlate position changes with traffic fluctuations. The number in position one means something precise and consistent.</p>
        <p>AEO measurement is less standardised but no less trackable. The primary metrics are:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Featured snippet ownership</strong> — what percentage of your target queries result in your content being shown in position zero. Tools like Semrush and Ahrefs track snippet ownership at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>People Also Ask appearances</strong> — how many PAA expansions across your keyword set draw from your pages. Each PAA slot is a separate answer selection opportunity.</li>
          <li><strong>AI Overview citations</strong> — how frequently your pages are cited in Google's AI-generated summary responses. Google Search Console is beginning to surface this data; third-party AI visibility platforms supplement it.</li>
          <li><strong>Voice answer share</strong> — harder to track at scale, but manually testable: query voice assistants for your target queries and record which source they cite.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The practical implication for reporting: an AEO programme may improve answer selection rate while organic click-through traffic declines, because winning the featured snippet often reduces clicks (users get the answer without visiting the page). Reporting on AEO requires framing visibility and authority alongside traffic, rather than treating traffic reduction as evidence of failure.</p>

        <!-- 6. Voice and snippets -->
        <h2 id="voice-and-snippets" class="anchor-top">Voice Search and Featured Snippets: The AEO-Specific Surfaces</h2>
        <p><strong>Featured snippets and voice search are the two answer surfaces that most clearly distinguish AEO from traditional SEO — both deliver direct answers, neither requires the user to click, and neither is primarily determined by traditional SEO ranking signals.</strong></p>
        <p>Featured snippets are the original answer engine. Google introduced them as a way to answer queries directly in search results rather than forcing users to navigate away to find simple information. They appear above the first organic result — often called "position zero" — and are selected by Google's algorithm based on passage relevance, content structure, and page authority. A page ranking in position four can displace a position-one page in the featured snippet if its content is more directly structured for extraction.</p>
        <p>Voice search operates on an even more concentrated model. Google Assistant, Amazon Alexa, and Apple Siri each select a single source for voice answers. There is no second result. If your content is not selected, it is simply absent from the voice channel. Voice queries are disproportionately local, conversational, and question-based — "what's the best time to plant tomatoes," "how long does a passport take to arrive" — making AEO especially important for businesses whose customers use voice for research or purchasing decisions.</p>
        <p>Google's AI Overviews represent the evolution of featured snippets: instead of extracting a single passage, the AI synthesises a multi-paragraph answer from multiple sources and attributes each claim. Winning an AI Overview citation requires the same structural signals as featured snippets — clarity, conciseness, question-heading alignment — but also requires that your content makes specific, well-grounded claims that the AI can use as building blocks in its synthesis. This overlap with <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Generative Engine Optimisation (GEO)</a> is where AEO and GEO converge most directly.</p>

        <!-- 7. Shared foundation -->
        <h2 id="shared-foundation" class="anchor-top">The Shared Foundation</h2>
        <p><strong>AEO does not replace SEO — it extends it. The technical and authority foundations that SEO builds are prerequisites for AEO, making the two disciplines interdependent rather than interchangeable.</strong></p>
        <p>Answer engines cannot select content from pages they cannot crawl and index. A slow, poorly structured, or robots.txt-blocked page is invisible to both traditional search rankings and answer selection. Technical SEO hygiene — canonical URLs, clean site architecture, fast load times, mobile responsiveness — is the baseline for both disciplines.</p>
        <p>Topical authority matters equally in both. An answer engine is unlikely to select a page from a domain that has published one article on a subject, when a competitor domain has fifty well-researched articles establishing it as the authoritative reference in the field. Building topical authority through consistent, expert content creation is an SEO strategy that directly supports AEO outcomes.</p>
        <p>Backlinks and domain trust, while less directly relevant to AEO's passage-level extraction signals, provide the baseline credibility that makes content eligible for selection. Emerging or low-authority domains face higher bars for featured snippet selection regardless of content structure. The authority that SEO accumulates over years is the condition of possibility for AEO success.</p>
        <p>The practical consequence: brands launching an AEO programme without strong SEO foundations will see limited results. The right sequencing is to establish technical health and topical authority through SEO, then layer AEO structural patterns on top. For brands with mature SEO programmes, the incremental investment in AEO-specific structure is relatively modest and the return — answer selection across dozens of high-intent queries — can be substantial. Explore our <a href="/aeo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO services</a> or the <a href="/aeo-best-practices/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO best practices guide</a> to understand the specific structural changes involved.</p>
        <p>For the broader picture of how both AEO and traditional SEO relate to AI-powered search platforms including ChatGPT and Perplexity, the <a href="/geo-vs-seo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO vs SEO guide</a> maps the full landscape.</p>

      </div>

